# The `DAGTypeLegalizer` Class Reference

<DoxygenPage pluginConfig={pluginConfig}>

This takes an arbitrary <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/selectiondag">SelectionDAG</a> as input and hacks on it until only value types the target machine can handle are left. <a href="#details">More...</a>

## Description {#details}

This takes an arbitrary <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/selectiondag">SelectionDAG</a> as input and hacks on it until only value types the target machine can handle are left.

This involves promoting small sizes to large sizes or splitting up large values into small values.

Definition at line 31 of file <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/codegen/lib/codegen/selectiondag/legalizetypes-h">LegalizeTypes.h</a>.

The specified node is the root of a subtree of potentially new nodes.

Correct any processed operands (this may change the node) and calculate the NodeId. If the node itself changes to a processed node, it is not remapped - the caller needs to take care of this. Returns the potentially changed node.

Replace the node&#39;s results with custom code provided by the target and return &quot;true&quot;, or do nothing and return &quot;false&quot;.

The last parameter is FALSE if we are dealing with a node with legal result types and illegal operand. The second parameter denotes the type of illegal OperandNo in that case. ExpandIntegerResult - This method is called when the specified result of the specified node is found to need expansion.

At this point, the node may also have invalid operands or may have other results that need promotion, we just know that (at least) one result needs expansion.

This performs an expansion of the integer result for a fixed point multiplication.

The default expansion performs rounding down towards negative infinity, though targets that do care about rounding should specify a target hook for rounding and provide their own expansion or lowering of fixed point multiplication to be consistent with rounding.

Given a processed operand <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a> which was expanded into two floating-point values of half the size, this returns the two halves.

The low bits of <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a> are exactly equal to the bits of Lo; the high bits exactly equal Hi. ### GetPromotedInteger() {#a3a0b9d6b90d9aeb452da517016651d70}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>SDValue llvm::DAGTypeLegalizer::GetPromotedInteger (<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sdvalue">SDValue</a> Op)</>}
  labels = {["inline"]}>
Given a processed operand <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a> which was promoted to a larger integer type, this returns the promoted value.

The low bits of the promoted value corresponding to the original type are exactly equal to <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a>. The extra bits contain rubbish, so the promoted value may need to be zero- or sign-extended from the original type before it is usable (the helpers SExtPromotedInteger and ZExtPromotedInteger can do this for you). For example, if <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a> is an i16 and was promoted to an i32, then this method returns an i32, the lower 16 bits of which coincide with <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a>, and the upper 16 bits of which contain rubbish.

### GetSplitVector() {#a4419495c0e948b5bf96390f5dae94007}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>void DAGTypeLegalizer::GetSplitVector (<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sdvalue">SDValue</a> Op, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sdvalue">SDValue</a> &amp; Lo, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sdvalue">SDValue</a> &amp; Hi)</>}>
Given a processed vector <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a> which was split into vectors of half the size, this method returns the halves.

The first elements of <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a> coincide with the elements of Lo; the remaining elements of <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a> coincide with the elements of Hi: <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a> is what you would get by concatenating Lo and Hi. For example, if <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a> is a v8i32 that was split into two v4i32&#39;s, then this method returns the two v4i32&#39;s, with Lo corresponding to the first 4 elements of <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a>, and Hi to the last 4 elements.

### GetWidenedVector() {#a06f4708abd50e9d4291e7600fe0aea64}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>SDValue llvm::DAGTypeLegalizer::GetWidenedVector (<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/sdvalue">SDValue</a> Op)</>}
  labels = {["inline"]}>
Given a processed vector <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a> which was widened into a larger vector, this method returns the larger vector.

The elements of the returned vector consist of the elements of <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a> followed by elements containing rubbish. For example, if <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a> is a v2i32 that was widened to a v4i32, then this method returns a v4i32 for which the first two elements are the same as those of <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#ab471937b9a227e70c7fe8bd9604014d6">Op</a>, while the last two elements contain rubbish.
